result.execSummary:
The defendant Johnathan Earl Coleman-Wilks was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case. One or more other charges in this case were dismissed. The dismissed charges were not proven and have no legal effect. Johnathan Earl Coleman-Wilks is presumed innocent of the dismissed charges.

  • Johnathan Earl Coleman-Wilks was found guilty of Harboring/Aiding a Felon [Modifiers: Party to a Crime, Use of a Dangerous Weapon], a class I felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.47(1)(a).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

The Court grants expungement upon successful completion of all conditions of probation.

miscConds.notes:
Pay all supervision fees.
Provide a DNA sample - pay surcharge.
Pay all applicable mandatory surcharges, fees, assessments, and costs by the end of probation period - any remaining balance to convert to civil judgment.
The Court ordered restitution set at zero.
If revoked, the Court ordered all financial obligations to be paid through collection of sums by the Department of Corrections from 25% of prison funds and as a condition of extended supervision. Any remaining balance to convert to a civil judgment.

Obtain/maintain full time employment or full time school with part time employment.
Obtain high school diploma or in the alternative, obtain a GED or HSED.
Defendant is informed he may not possess and/or own any firearms.

No illegal drug dealing or association with drug community (drug users/dealers/houses).
No new law violations that rise to the level of probable cause..
No contact with victims, DeAngelo T.G. and Jeremy M.

Cooperate with all rules set forth by the probation agent.
Defendant is informed he may not vote in any election until his civil rights have been reinstated.

Obtain AODA assessment and if necessary complete follow-up care/treatment.
Absolute sobriety with random urine screens and breathalyzer tests.
